    research: `Custom herbal compounding in Dr. Hendry's in-house pharmacy allows formula modification at the constituent level — adding, removing, or adjusting individual herbs within a classical base formula to match a patient's current presentation with a precision that pre-made products cannot achieve. This reflects the classical Chinese medical principle of sui zheng jia jian (modifying a base formula according to the presenting pattern). Zhang W et al. (Maturitas, 2007) demonstrated that Chinese herbal medicine improved bone mineral density in menopausal women, an effect attributable to phytoestrogenic and osteoblast-stimulating herbs whose dosing must be calibrated to the individual's hormonal profile. Zhu X et al. (Cochrane Database Syst Rev, 2008) found that custom-prescribed formulas for dysmenorrhea outperformed standardized formulas, consistent with the clinical principle that individualized prescribing produces superior outcomes. The in-house pharmacy sources pharmaceutical-grade granule extracts from licensed manufacturers with heavy metal testing, pesticide screening, and authenticated species identification — quality controls that are absent from most retail herbal products. Fugh-Berman A and Ernst E (Br J Clin Pharmacol, 2001;52(5):587-595) established that herb-drug interactions require systematic assessment, reinforcing the necessity of professional oversight in custom compounding.`,
    comparison: {
      title: "Custom-Compounded Formulas vs. Standardized Nutraceutical Products",
      text: `Standardized nutraceutical products offer consistency: each capsule contains the same dose of the same extract. This standardization is valuable for research purposes and for patients who self-select supplements based on published evidence for a specific compound. However, it imposes a one-size prescription on a population with diverse presentations. Two patients with the same diagnosis of hypothyroid-associated fatigue may have entirely different Chinese medical patterns: one presenting with blood deficiency and liver qi stagnation, the other with kidney yang deficiency and spleen qi vacuity. The same standardized adaptogen blend addresses neither pattern specifically. A custom formula compounds a different herbal combination for each, directly targeting the physiological terrain identified through clinical examination. Additionally, patients on thyroid medication, antidepressants, or anticoagulants require formula customization that removes herbs with known pharmacokinetic interactions — a safety requirement that standardized products are not designed to accommodate. Custom compounding integrates therapeutic precision with pharmacological safety in a way that no retail product can replicate, and the in-house pharmacy makes this level of care available at every clinical visit.`,
    },

